<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-03-31T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-03-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="255" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d255">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/3–3149: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-03-31">March 31,
                                1949</date>.<lb/>[Received March 31—6:37 a. m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>685. Vernacular press March 26 reported Executive Yuan Council at first
                            session March 24 decided retain its Chiefs of Ministries and Political
                            Vice Ministers in Nanking, while retaining administrative units and
                            Administrative Vice Ministers in Canton.</p>
                        <p>Sent Department 685; repeated Shanghai 315, Canton unnumbered.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>